The UK's Department of Health and Social Care (DHSC) helps people to live more independent, healthier lives for longer. Our official development assistance (ODA) funded programmes take this objective beyond the UK to address global health challenges for the benefit of people living in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs).

The UK Public Health Rapid Support Team has been established with the purpose to research and investigate possible or known disease outbreaks in Official Development Assistance (ODA) eligible countries and to help control such threats before they might become a national or international health emergency. The project has the primary purpose of ensuring that the United Kingdom has a standing capacity of multidisciplinary public health professionals and researchers that can be ready to deploy within 48 hours to a possible or known disease outbreak in a country that is eligible for ODA, as defined by the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).

The objectives of this activity are detailed under Joint Global Health Trials Initiative (GB-GOV-10-JGHT), reported by DHSC.

1) Create a new Global Research Group on dementia risk reduction and improved post-diagnostic care to map existing dementia research and care in partner LMIC. 2) Develop simple tools to identify people at high risk of developing dementia and those with undetected dementia. 3) Establish dementia risk reduction research in LMIC by setting up and piloting an intervention to reduce dementia risk. 4) Determine efficient and feasible dementia care models for LMICs and transferable educational initiatives for a skilled workforce. 5) Develop an impact strategy for each partner LMIC, including research priorities, service organisation and workforce development.

1) Coordination - To build increasing levels of research collaboration across the member agencies; 2) Awareness - To create a platform for general awareness raising and to conduct outreach beyond the original founding members; 3) Capacity-building - To develop and maintain global knowledge-sharing platforms in the conduct and management of chronic non-communicable diseases research in low- and middle-income countries.

1) Building on established academic and surgical networks and working with local ministries of health, NGOs, and private healthcare providers to conduct collaborative research. 2) Undertaking social science research to better understand local healthcare systems, including cultural and social attitudes to surgery, defining the unmet surgical needs, and assessing existing research strengths and capacity. 3) Using NIHR medical technology capability (Leeds NIHR Healthcare Technology Co-operative and Leeds Diagnostic Evaluation Centre) to develop disruptive, yet affordable, solutions to unmet surgical needs relevant to local healthcare settings. 4) Undertaking clinical evaluations, including cost-effectiveness assessment, in partnership with local researchers to inform wider adoption. 5) Establishing an advocacy programme, linked to other global health organisations, to influence awareness of health inequalities and promote the impact of our research.
